import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming 'df' is your pandas DataFrame loaded earlier

scatter_plot = sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Rotation Speed (rpm)', y='Torque (Nm)',
                size=32, alpha=.8, hue="Machine Status")
plt.title('Rotation Speed (rpm) vs Torque (Nm) by Machine Status') # Optional: add a title
plt.xlabel('Rotation Speed (rpm)') # Optional: label x-axis
plt.ylabel('Torque (Nm)') # Optional: label y-axis

# Get the legend handles and labels from the scatter plot
handles, labels = scatter_plot.get_legend_handles_labels()

# Find the handles and labels corresponding to the 'Machine Status' hue
# This assumes the hue legend is the first or primary legend generated by seaborn
# You might need to inspect the handles and labels list if there are multiple legends
hue_handles = handles[:len(df['Machine Status'].unique())] # Assuming hue legend comes first
hue_labels = labels[:len(df['Machine Status'].unique())] # Assuming hue legend comes first

# Create a new legend using only the hue handles and labels
plt.legend(hue_handles, hue_labels, title='Machine Status')

plt.show() # Make sure to show the plot

In [146]:
import pandas as pd

# Filter rows where Machine Status is 1
df_status_1 = XY_train[XY_train['Machine Status'] == 1]

# Determine the number of samples to bootstrap
# Let's say we want to have the same number of status 1 rows as status 0 rows
target_count = XY_train['Machine Status'].value_counts().max()
num_samples = target_count - len(df_status_1)

# Perform bootstrapping with replacement
df_bootstrapped_status_1 = df_status_1.sample(n=num_samples,
                                replace=True, random_state=42) # Added random_state for reproducibility

# Concatenate the bootstrapped samples back to the original dataframe
XY_train = pd.concat([XY_train, df_bootstrapped_status_1], ignore_index=True)

# Verify the new counts
print(XY_train["Machine Status"].value_counts())

0    13549
1    13549

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Identify the features to scale
columms_to_scale = ["Rotation Speed (rpm)","Torque (Nm)","Tool Wear (min)"]

# Initialize the StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()

# Fit the scaler on the training data and transform it
X_train[columms_to_scale] = scaler.fit_transform(X_train[columms_to_scale])

# Transform the test data using the same scaler
X_test[columms_to_scale] = scaler.transform(X_test[columms_to_scale])

print("Scaled X_train:")

Modelling¶

In [152]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

knnmodel = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
knnmodel.fit(X_train, y_train)
cv_score = cross_val_score(knnmodel, X_train, y_train, cv=5)
#print(cv_score)
ytest_hat = knnmodel.predict(X_test)

print("Train Score=",knnmodel.score(X_train,y_train))
print("Cross-validation score=",cv_score.mean())
print("Test score=",accuracy_score(y_test,ytest_hat))

In [155]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

params = {
    'n_neighbors': [3, 5, 10, 20, 100],
}

knnmodel = KNeighborsClassifier()
grid_search = GridSearchCV(knnmodel, params, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best parameters:", best_params)
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_

cv_score = cross_val_score(best_model, X_train, y_train, cv=5)
#print(cv_score)
ytest_hat = best_model.predict(X_test)

print("Train Score=",best_model.score(X_train,y_train))
print("Cross-validation score=",cv_score.mean())
print("Test score=",accuracy_score(y_test,ytest_hat))

Best parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3}
Train Score= 0.9974167835264596
Cross-validation score= 0.987748185453805
Test score= 0.9811751283513976

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score
# Calculate ROC curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, ytest_hat)
# Calculate AUC
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, ytest_hat)
# Plot ROC curve
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve (AUC = %0.2f)' % auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--') # plot the diagonal line
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Calculate the confusion matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, ytest_hat)

# Create a heatmap using seaborn
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='viridis', cbar=False,
            xticklabels=['Predicted 0', 'Predicted 1'],
            yticklabels=['Actual 0', 'Actual 1'],
            annot_kws={'size': 14})
plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
plt.ylabel('True Label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()
